// Yes — this is absolutely possible. High level notes and a minimal plan
// for making the cursor in the email view interactive with j/k/h/l:
//
// 1) Conceptual model
// - Keep bodyScroll as the index of the first visible line (already present).
// - Add a bodyCursor (int) that is the selected line index relative to the
//   visible window (0..visibleLines-1). This lets the user move the cursor
//   independently of the scroll offset.
// - Optionally add bodyCol (int) if you want character-level movement (h/l).
//
// 2) Key handling (minimal change)
// - j: if bodyCursor < visibleLines-1 and start+bodyCursor < len(lines)-1 -> bodyCursor++
//      else if at bottom of visible window and start+bodyCursor < len(lines)-1 -> bodyScroll++
// - k: mirror of j (decrement cursor or scroll up)
// - h/l: adjust bodyCol clamped to 0..len(selectedLine)
// - Make sure to clamp bodyCursor and bodyScroll to file bounds after each change.
//
// 3) Rendering changes (minimal)
// - After calling renderer.Render and building the lines slice, compute
//   start := m.bodyScroll and selectedIndex := start + m.bodyCursor.
// - For line-level cursor: prefix the visible line at selectedIndex with the
//   cursor marker (">" currently) instead of always modifying lines[m.bodyScroll].
// - For character-level cursor: insert or style a single rune at bodyCol on
//   the selected visual line. Note: if the renderer emits ANSI styling, measuring
//   and inserting by visual columns becomes trickier — use lipgloss.Width or
//   strip ANSI to compute rune-width correctly (or render a plain-text version
//   for cursor math).
//
// 4) Wrapping and visual lines
// - If your renderer produces long lines that wrap in the viewport, you have
//   two choices: treat wrapped visual lines as separate entries (pre-wrap with
//   the viewport width) or keep logical lines and maintain a mapping from
//   visual-row -> (logical line, column offset). The simpler path is to wrap
//   to viewport width before building the visible lines slice.
//
// 5) UX and toggles
// - Consider a mode toggle (e.g., pressing v or i) to switch between
//   'scroll-only' and 'interactive-cursor' behavior. That avoids accidental
//   activation when a user only expects to scroll.
//
// 6) Minimal incremental implementation plan
// - Add m.bodyCursor int (init 0) and optionally m.bodyCol int.
// - Update the "j"/"k" handler to move bodyCursor first and then bodyScroll
//   when necessary.
// - Update View() to mark the selected visible line: use selected := start + m.bodyCursor
//   and modify that visible line to include the cursor marker.
// - Later: add h/l handling and handle ANSI/wrapped-line complexities.
//
// Summary: start with a line-level bodyCursor (simple, low-risk). Character
// level (h/l) is fully feasible but requires extra handling for wrapped lines
// and ANSI-marked output — do that after the line-level cursor works.
